BirdNET to CSV:

An alternative to BirdNET Analyzer for processing WAV files of bird calls into a CSV of identified species.

I've created a software tool that is able to feed large amounts of bird call audio files to BirdNET to return a comma-separated value file of the identified birds for researchers to analyze. The tool, currently called "BirdNET to CSV", overcomes limits to the number of files that can be analyzed per job and provides a minimalist alternative to Cornell's BirdNET Analyzer. This project was developed to support Colorado State University and the US Forest Service's research into how wildlife return the locations of large wildfires, specifically the locations of the 2020 Cameron Peak, East Troublesome, and Mullen wildfires which are shown in the map below. With over 500,000 acres burnt and thousands of hours of audio to process, my project parners grew frustrated with having to feed data to BirdNET Analyzer in 50 file increments. So my goal was to give them time back by creating a program to feed their data files through BirdNET's python library that they could run in the background unsupervised.

WARNING:param.GeoOverlayPlot03197: Due to internal constraints, when aspect and width/height is set, the bokeh backend uses those values as frame_width/frame_height instead. This ensures the aspect is respected, but means that the plot might be slightly larger than anticipated. Set the frame_width/frame_height explicitly to suppress this warning.

How it works

BirdNET to CSV is an executable file that is saved to and ran from the folder containing all the audio files that you want to have analyzed. The files can be within subfolders for your own organization, as the program will recursively search for any .wav file that exists in the folder it is ran from. Then after checking that any of the files have not been analyzed already, the files will be analyzed by the BirdNET machine learning algorithm and then appended to a CSV file. Because those results are appended to the CSV file intermittently, the user doesn't have to worry about losing progress in the event of a crash or power outage! Just restart the program to pick up where it left off. As the BirdNET python library does not have all the functionality of BirdNET Analyzer, BirdNET to CSV is a minimalist application that does not take much time to configure. The user does retain the ability to filter the possible bird species by location given by latitude and longitude. Inputting those values is the only interaction the user has to make with the application.

But how fast is it?

I was curious about how BirdNET to CSV compared to BirdNET Analyzer and did an impromptu speed test with various numbers of files per job. The results are in the graph below. With just one file, BirdNET to CSV was able to start up much quicker than BirdNET Analyzer and maintained that speed (~52 seconds per file analyzed) no matter how many files it was analyzing. However BirdNET Analyzer uses multiple CPU threads to organize the tasks that the computer performs much more efficiently, and that becomes apparent as BirdNET Analyzer was able to increase its speed of analysis to below 40 seconds per file analyzed when it was given 50 files to work through. Despite this, BirdNET to CSV fills a niche of being an easy to use tool that can run in the background, such as when my project partners left it to run for two days while they went out into the field to continue collecting data. Hours of time was returned to them.

What does the future hold?

Being able to process multiple files simultaneously would greatly improve the speed of BirdNET to CSV, so I would like to adapt the application to use the birdnet library's multiprocessing function. Additionally, I need to create a MacOS distribution. I created the current distribution with PyInstaller since it packages in the version of the python environment that I used to create it. That made it easier for my partners to use since they didn't have to worry about creating a python environment or installing dependent software.
